{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01A84mb1UGLFdggHJtXjX99P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"It's a classic durable queue. Classic queues in RabbitMQ are stored on a single node (the queue master/leader). Since we're doing rolling upgrades, the queue data should be preserved as long as:\n1. We don't lose the node that holds the queue data\n2. The queue is durable (it is!)\n\nFor rolling upgrades with classic queues, we need to be careful. The safest approach is to upgrade one node at a time (rolling), because:\n- Classic durable queues survive node restarts (data is on disk)\n- When a node restarts, it rejoins the cluster and gets its queue data from disk\n- This rolling upgrade approach is safe here.\n\nNow I need to update the ConfigMap. The `queue_master_locator` setting is deprecated in RabbitMQ 3.12 and replaced with `queue_leader_locator`. The value `min-masters` has been renamed to `balanced` in newer versions, so I'll need to account for that change depending on which version we're targeting.\n\nI should update the ConfigMap proactively before starting the upgrade to use the newer configuration keys that are compatible with 3.12 and beyond, which will prevent compatibility issues as we move through the versions. the new settings. I should update the ConfigMap to use `queue_leader_locator = client-local` instead of the deprecated `queue_master_locator = min-masters`, which will ensure compatibility across the upgrade path from 3.12 to 4.x without triggering startup errors.\n\nActually, I need to verify whether intermediate versions will accept the new config parameter—if 3.12 doesn't recognize `queue_leader_locator`, I might need to upgrade first and then update the configuration afterward to avoid compatibility issues.\n\nThe safest sequence would be upgrading through each version step-by-step, then updating the ConfigMap to remove the deprecated parameter before jumping to 4.0, 